Load gtemp.csv. from https://nmimoto.github.io/datasets/. The data contains 130 annual global temperature readings. Theres no link on the page, and you have to load it directly to R. Turn the data into ts object in R.

library(forecast)
source('https://nmimoto.github.io/R/TS-00.txt')

Temp = read.csv("https://nmimoto.github.io/datasets/gtemp.csv")
head(Temp)

a) Perform stationairty analysis

using Stationairty.tests(). What is the right value of \(d\) if we are to model this data using ARIMA(\(p,d,q\))?

Stationarity.tests(Y)
## Warning in pp.test(A): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## Warning in kpss.test(A): p-value smaller than printed p-value
##        KPSS   ADF   PP
## p-val: 0.01 0.706 0.01
  ## small-large-small.  They are mixed for d=0.

plot(diff(Y), type='o')

b) Find best ARIMA model

that fits the data, using auto.arima() and Arima(),

FitA1 = auto.arima(Y, d=0, stepwise=FALSE, approximation=FALSE)

c) Fit a linear trend

to the undifferenced data using lm(). How is the fit of [linear trend + stationary error] model to this data?

Reg1 = lm(Y ~ time(Y))
Stationarity.tests(Reg1$residuals)
## Warning in pp.test(A): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## Warning in kpss.test(A): p-value greater than printed p-value
##        KPSS   ADF   PP
## p-val:  0.1 0.706 0.01
  ## ADF test says residuals are not statonary.
  ## [LT + Xt] model does not look good.



d) What can you say about the form of the trend

in the data from what you see in (b) and (c)? Do you support deterministic trend or random trend for the model of this data?

Because of (c), we have to go with ARIMA(p,1,q) model from (b), which implies that the trend is random rather than deterministic.

e) State the name of your final model in your R script.

(e.g.Fit1, Fit2, etc.) Express it using mathematical equations, using as original observations. List all parameters and their estimates.

##N#  My Final model is FitB1, which is ARIMA(1,1,3) w drift. Because it has
## all parameters significant and is with lower AICc.
## ARIMA(2,1,3) is arguablly better model, because AR2 there is significant.
## However, this model has MA1 insignificant.
## For forecasting pourpose, the two models will produces similar result.

FitB1
## Series: Y 
## ARIMA(1,1,3) with drift 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ar1     ma1      ma2      ma3   drift
##       -0.9376  0.4846  -0.6341  -0.2857  0.0065
## s.e.   0.0946  0.1165   0.0955   0.0866  0.0025
## 
## sigma^2 = 0.009108:  log likelihood = 122.17
## AIC=-232.34   AICc=-231.66   BIC=-215.19
##N#  Final Model is ARMA(1,1,3) w drift.
###  Y_t = observation
###  Y_t = W_t + X'_t   where W_t is RW with drift (delta)
###  X_t = Y_t - Y_{t-1} + delta
###  X_t = (phi1) X_{t-1} + e_t + (theta1) e_{t-1} + (theta2) e_{t-2} + (theta3) e_{t-3}
###  e_t = WN(0, sigma)
###
###
###  delta_hat 0.0065
###  phi1_hat  -0.9376
###  the1_hat   0.4846
###  the2_hat  -0.6341
###  the3_hat  -0.2857
###  sigma_hat  sqrt(0.009108) = 0.0954358

g) Perform retroactive rolling 1-step prediction

for the last 20 observations of the data using your final model. Comment on the prediction performance.

                             window.size=110,
                             Arima.order=c(1,1,3),
                             include.drift=TRUE)
